     <p><strong><p><strong>Alva Noë, <em>The Entanglement: How Art and Philosophy Make Us Who We Are</em>, Princeton University Press, 2023, 288pp., $27.95 (hbk), ISBN 9780691188812.</strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Guy Dammann, Uppsala University</strong></p>
     <p>One of the features of philosophical discourse that distinguishes it from most other branches of scientific and humanistic enquiry is the lack of widespread agreement about basic terms and concepts. Philosophy is less often a matter of adopting and refining a methodology and applying it to the evidence than of asking what is meant by concepts such as “matter” and “evidence” in the first place. And if this feature is distinctive of philosophy as a whole, then it perhaps reaches its extreme in philosophical aesthetics, where everything from rudimentary concepts such as aesthetic judgement and aesthetic experience to its very scope—where the boundary between aesthetic and non-aesthetic lies—seems constantly to be up for grabs. Indeed, the only claim likely to unite a group of aestheticians...
